1
00:00:33,625 --> 00:00:35,291
[CIKAPASI]
We finally found you!

2
00:00:35,375 --> 00:00:38,208
We've been looking all over
for you since Otaru.

3
00:00:39,291 --> 00:00:40,125
You have been?

4
00:00:40,208 --> 00:00:41,708
[ALL]
Huh?

5
00:00:41,791 --> 00:00:44,208
Yeah, we even met a couple
Ainu hunters over there

6
00:00:44,291 --> 00:00:45,708
and asked if they'd seen you.

7
00:00:45,791 --> 00:00:47,875
♪

8
00:00:47,958 --> 00:00:50,750
Hey. Have either of you seen
an Ainu girl around here?

9
00:00:50,833 --> 00:00:52,375
[BOTH]
Hmm?

10
00:00:52,458 --> 00:00:55,000
She'd most likely be traveling
with a Japanese man

11
00:00:55,083 --> 00:00:56,375
with a scar on his face.

12
00:00:57,500 --> 00:00:58,625
Oh.

13
00:00:58,708 --> 00:01:00,083
Sounds like the one we just saw.

14
00:01:00,166 --> 00:01:01,541
[gasps]

15
00:01:01,625 --> 00:01:03,291
They both seemed
really impressed

16
00:01:03,375 --> 00:01:05,750
that you'd been able
to make it all this way.

17
00:01:05,833 --> 00:01:08,208
They even invited us to come
visit their kotan.

18
00:01:08,291 --> 00:01:09,666
And they just hunted a bear.

19
00:01:09,750 --> 00:01:11,000
-So you know what that means.
-[gasps]

20
00:01:11,083 --> 00:01:12,416
Right, let's go.

21
00:01:12,500 --> 00:01:14,250
There's bear stew
waiting for us all.

22
00:01:14,333 --> 00:01:15,875
If I'm being honest,

23
00:01:15,958 --> 00:01:17,541
I'd much rather go hit
the local bars

24
00:01:17,625 --> 00:01:19,458
with Inkarmat's money.

25
00:01:19,541 --> 00:01:21,083
Leave her alone.

26
00:01:21,166 --> 00:01:23,333
You can't treat her like that,
she's a part of my family.

27
00:01:23,416 --> 00:01:25,416
-[ASIRPA sighs]
-Your what now?

28
00:01:25,500 --> 00:01:27,916
Yeah. She's nice to me
and looks after me

29
00:01:28,000 --> 00:01:30,125
and she doesn't get mad
when I touch her boobs.

30
00:01:30,208 --> 00:01:31,958
And Tanigaki Nispa
is her gigolo.

31
00:01:32,041 --> 00:01:34,125
That is correct.

32
00:01:36,583 --> 00:01:38,208
[TANIGAKI]
What are they doing here?

33
00:01:40,666 --> 00:01:41,666
Gigolo?

34
00:01:41,750 --> 00:01:43,333
[TANIGAKI]
Um, no.

35
00:03:14,416 --> 00:03:16,833
[singing in Ainu]

36
00:03:21,708 --> 00:03:23,208
[children chuckling]

37
00:03:25,041 --> 00:03:26,166
Hmm?

38
00:03:27,916 --> 00:03:31,291
So, you found them.
Glad you made it.

39
00:03:31,375 --> 00:03:32,583
[HUNTER 1]
Just in time.

40
00:03:32,666 --> 00:03:34,750
The Kamuy Hopunire's
about to start.

41
00:03:34,833 --> 00:03:36,791
[HUNTER 2]
Enjoy yourselves.

42
00:03:36,875 --> 00:03:41,000
It's a ceremony, and it means
"The Setting-Off of Gods."

43
00:03:41,083 --> 00:03:44,375
So they send off the spirit
of the hunted bear.

44
00:03:44,458 --> 00:03:46,416
It's a different ritual
than an iomante,

45
00:03:46,500 --> 00:03:48,875
where they send off a bear
that was raised in a cage.

46
00:03:48,958 --> 00:03:51,583
[MAN]
Oh-oh-oh-hoy!

47
00:03:51,666 --> 00:03:54,708
Ah-ah-ah-hoy!

48
00:03:54,791 --> 00:03:57,000
Oh-oh-oh-hoy!

49
00:03:57,083 --> 00:04:00,083
Oh-oh-oh-hoy!

50
00:04:00,166 --> 00:04:02,291
That's called an "okokokse."

51
00:04:02,375 --> 00:04:05,958
They shout out to tell
the god of fire about the bear.

52
00:04:06,041 --> 00:04:09,666
The kamuy are the things
beyond human control.

53
00:04:09,750 --> 00:04:12,916
Some things help us,
other things bring us disaster.

54
00:04:13,958 --> 00:04:16,333
Fire is a critical part
of our lives,

55
00:04:16,416 --> 00:04:18,375
and blades slice
cleanly through things

56
00:04:18,458 --> 00:04:19,750
we can't cut on our own.

57
00:04:19,833 --> 00:04:21,625
So they have kamuy in them.

58
00:04:21,708 --> 00:04:24,041
Trees are kamuy
that sit on the mountains.

59
00:04:24,125 --> 00:04:27,166
Bad weather and plague
are beyond human control,

60
00:04:27,250 --> 00:04:28,791
so they're kamuy, too.

61
00:04:30,000 --> 00:04:31,875
But it's not that we believe

62
00:04:31,958 --> 00:04:34,541
these things are any greater
than humanity.

63
00:04:34,625 --> 00:04:37,458
We think of them
as equals to us.

64
00:04:37,541 --> 00:04:39,333
We believe that when hunting,

65
00:04:39,416 --> 00:04:41,875
it's not the arrows
hitting our prey,

66
00:04:41,958 --> 00:04:43,958
it's the kamuy
running into them.

67
00:04:45,125 --> 00:04:46,916
We invite them to our world,

68
00:04:47,000 --> 00:04:49,291
and in exchange
for their meat and pelts,

69
00:04:49,375 --> 00:04:51,583
they ask for sake and tobacco.

70
00:04:51,666 --> 00:04:53,625
Things that only we can make.

71
00:04:53,708 --> 00:04:56,583
Then we send off the kamuy
with a proper ritual.

72
00:04:56,666 --> 00:04:59,000
In the hopes they'll tell
the other kamuy

73
00:04:59,083 --> 00:05:01,875
the human world
is a good place for them to go.

74
00:05:01,958 --> 00:05:04,250
If we don't treat them properly,

75
00:05:04,333 --> 00:05:06,291
they'll never come back
to our world.

76
00:05:07,791 --> 00:05:11,416
After this, the bear's head will
be taken to an outdoor altar

77
00:05:11,500 --> 00:05:13,083
decorated with inaw.

78
00:05:13,166 --> 00:05:14,666
Inaw are shaven sticks

79
00:05:14,750 --> 00:05:17,125
that we give
to the kamuy as an offering.

80
00:05:19,000 --> 00:05:21,916
Over time,
as it collects inaw,

81
00:05:22,000 --> 00:05:23,833
its status
in its own world grows.

82
00:05:23,916 --> 00:05:25,750
It's said that the inaw
we give it

83
00:05:25,833 --> 00:05:27,833
transform into silver and gold,

84
00:05:27,916 --> 00:05:30,000
becoming valuable treasures.

85
00:05:30,083 --> 00:05:33,708
Even in the afterlife,
we're driven by gold.

86
00:05:33,791 --> 00:05:37,000
Somehow, I'd hoped we'd be
better than that by then.

87
00:05:37,083 --> 00:05:39,416
♪

88
00:05:42,375 --> 00:05:44,083
[indistinct chatter]

89
00:05:48,833 --> 00:05:50,416
Will you stay here long?

90
00:05:50,500 --> 00:05:52,208
Well, that's not
really up to me.

91
00:05:52,291 --> 00:05:54,375
[SHIRAISHI groaning]

92
00:05:57,458 --> 00:05:58,916
That's delicious.

93
00:06:01,333 --> 00:06:03,041
[chuckles softly]

94
00:06:03,125 --> 00:06:04,833
[ASIRPA]
What's she thinking?

95
00:06:04,916 --> 00:06:06,083
I wonder.

96
00:06:06,166 --> 00:06:07,250
[TANIGAKI]
Asirpa.

97
00:06:08,916 --> 00:06:11,166
There's something
I need to tell you.

98
00:06:11,250 --> 00:06:13,583
I've come
because I have news about Huci.

99
00:06:18,500 --> 00:06:20,250
[snoring]

100
00:06:29,875 --> 00:06:31,041
[ASIRPA]
Huci.

101
00:06:33,833 --> 00:06:35,583
So we're really supposed
to believe

102
00:06:35,666 --> 00:06:37,250
that you came all the way
from Otaru

103
00:06:37,333 --> 00:06:39,833
just to tell her that,
Private Tanigaki?

104
00:06:39,916 --> 00:06:41,166
Something you wanna say?

105
00:06:41,250 --> 00:06:43,250
How about
if we don't play games?

106
00:06:43,333 --> 00:06:45,833
I know Tsurumi sent you here
just to watch me.

107
00:06:45,916 --> 00:06:47,250
No, you're wrong.

108
00:06:47,333 --> 00:06:49,583
I'm done with the Seventh,
with the whole army.

109
00:06:49,666 --> 00:06:51,458
That old lady helped me out,

110
00:06:51,541 --> 00:06:53,625
so I'm here
for her granddaughter.

111
00:06:53,708 --> 00:06:55,250
It's as simple as that.

112
00:06:55,333 --> 00:06:57,541
Not sure I believe you.

113
00:06:57,625 --> 00:06:59,916
You were one of Tsurumi's
most fervent followers

114
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:02,541
and you even killed three men
in the mountains, as I recall.

115
00:07:02,625 --> 00:07:04,166
Hmm...

116
00:07:04,250 --> 00:07:05,833
In the mountains?

117
00:07:05,916 --> 00:07:08,541
You're talking about the three
he was traveling with?

118
00:07:08,625 --> 00:07:11,375
If so, it was a bear
that killed them.

119
00:07:11,458 --> 00:07:13,166
I was there and I saw it.

120
00:07:13,250 --> 00:07:14,458
So I'm sure.

121
00:07:14,541 --> 00:07:15,833
A bear?

122
00:07:17,833 --> 00:07:18,750
Hmm.

123
00:07:18,833 --> 00:07:20,416
So the old lady just had a dream

124
00:07:20,500 --> 00:07:22,458
where she never saw
her granddaughter again?

125
00:07:22,541 --> 00:07:24,708
It was just a dream.

126
00:07:24,791 --> 00:07:26,916
You could've sent a damn letter.

127
00:07:27,000 --> 00:07:28,458
[ASIRPA]
We Ainu believe

128
00:07:28,541 --> 00:07:30,666
dreams are things the kamuy send

129
00:07:30,750 --> 00:07:32,333
when they're trying
to communicate.

130
00:07:32,416 --> 00:07:34,375
When they have something
to show us.

131
00:07:34,458 --> 00:07:38,416
I don't believe that now,
but Huci is one of the old Ainu.

132
00:07:39,708 --> 00:07:43,833
And once, long ago,
she had another dream.

133
00:07:45,458 --> 00:07:49,500
In this dream, her daughter
was surrounded by bears.

134
00:07:49,583 --> 00:07:52,625
They were sending her off
to the next world.

135
00:07:52,708 --> 00:07:54,208
According to Huci,

136
00:07:54,291 --> 00:07:58,333
soon after that,
my mother got sick and died.

137
00:07:58,416 --> 00:08:02,000
So that's why she always
believes her dreams.

138
00:08:02,083 --> 00:08:03,583
-Listen, Asirpa.
-Hmm?

139
00:08:03,666 --> 00:08:05,916
Do you just wanna head back?

140
00:08:06,000 --> 00:08:09,208
If she sees your face,
then surely that takes her dream

141
00:08:09,291 --> 00:08:11,875
out of the "prophecy" category,
doesn't it?

142
00:08:11,958 --> 00:08:13,291
She'll feel better.

143
00:08:16,208 --> 00:08:18,041
Don't force yourself to stay.

144
00:08:18,125 --> 00:08:19,291
[gasps]

145
00:08:20,333 --> 00:08:21,541
[sighs]

146
00:08:21,625 --> 00:08:24,125
Don't treat me like a child,
Sugimoto.

147
00:08:24,208 --> 00:08:25,666
I can't stop.

148
00:08:25,750 --> 00:08:27,791
I have to keep going now.

149
00:08:27,875 --> 00:08:29,666
I need to find the truth,

150
00:08:29,750 --> 00:08:32,791
then move forward
for the sake of my own dream.

151
00:08:32,875 --> 00:08:35,250
♪

152
00:08:38,666 --> 00:08:40,000
[snoring]

153
00:08:52,166 --> 00:08:54,500
Hey. Tanigaki Nispa.

154
00:08:54,583 --> 00:08:56,208
I've been wondering.

155
00:08:56,291 --> 00:08:57,750
That Murata gun,

156
00:08:57,833 --> 00:08:59,375
did it belong to Tetsuzou Nihei?

157
00:08:59,458 --> 00:09:00,750
[gasps]

158
00:09:00,833 --> 00:09:02,166
How did you know Nihei?

159
00:09:02,250 --> 00:09:04,166
We hunted bears together.

160
00:09:04,250 --> 00:09:05,916
Over a decade ago.

161
00:09:06,000 --> 00:09:07,583
He was so good at it.

162
00:09:07,666 --> 00:09:10,125
I'm still amazed there were
any bears left on that mountain.

163
00:09:12,416 --> 00:09:14,291
He died in those mountains.

164
00:09:14,375 --> 00:09:16,625
He had his gun on him.
I couldn't leave it.

165
00:09:16,708 --> 00:09:18,416
I would've done the same thing.

166
00:09:18,500 --> 00:09:22,750
Although, it must be challenging
using an old gun like that.

167
00:09:22,833 --> 00:09:24,458
Nihei changed me.

168
00:09:24,541 --> 00:09:27,541
From a soldier
back into a Matagi.

169
00:09:27,625 --> 00:09:29,708
I decided to carry it
so I'll never forget

170
00:09:29,791 --> 00:09:32,833
how to feel
when I shoot my prey.

171
00:09:32,916 --> 00:09:36,791
"You get one shot, so do it
right the first time." Right?

172
00:09:36,875 --> 00:09:38,083
[scoffs]

173
00:09:39,333 --> 00:09:40,958
See that on the barrel?

174
00:09:41,041 --> 00:09:43,166
Those seven little marks
he scratched out?

175
00:09:44,541 --> 00:09:46,458
Nihei once told me
what they meant.

176
00:09:48,500 --> 00:09:50,583
I've got a lot of kids,
no doubt about it,

177
00:09:50,666 --> 00:09:52,666
but I only ever had one son.

178
00:09:53,958 --> 00:09:55,333
This is the gun
he carried with him

179
00:09:55,416 --> 00:09:57,625
during the first
Sino-Japanese War.

180
00:09:57,708 --> 00:10:00,500
A friend of his gave it to me.

181
00:10:00,583 --> 00:10:02,333
And he told me each mark
on the stock

182
00:10:02,416 --> 00:10:04,666
represented an enemy
my son had shot.

183
00:10:06,000 --> 00:10:09,041
Maybe he just stopped counting
after the seventh.

184
00:10:09,125 --> 00:10:11,083
Or maybe he died shortly after.

185
00:10:12,250 --> 00:10:13,750
Either way, he wasn't the type

186
00:10:13,833 --> 00:10:15,791
who found any joy
shooting people.

187
00:10:15,875 --> 00:10:19,375
He was the kind that'd feel
guilty after killing someone.

188
00:10:19,458 --> 00:10:21,666
Never should've been a soldier.

189
00:10:21,750 --> 00:10:24,583
He should've just stayed home
and shot bears with me.

190
00:10:26,083 --> 00:10:28,166
♪

191
00:10:30,250 --> 00:10:31,541
-[leaves rustling]
-[BOTH] Huh?

192
00:10:33,625 --> 00:10:35,291
Ryu, is that you, boy?

193
00:10:35,375 --> 00:10:37,083
[barking]

194
00:10:38,958 --> 00:10:40,041
Ryu?

195
00:10:41,083 --> 00:10:42,916
[CIKAPASI]
Oh, wow! Look.

196
00:10:43,000 --> 00:10:46,625
Okay, yeah, what's Nihei's dog
doing here?

197
00:10:46,708 --> 00:10:48,166
Did you bring him with you?

198
00:10:48,250 --> 00:10:49,250
Actually, no.

199
00:10:49,333 --> 00:10:51,708
[SUGIMOTO gasps]
Oh, my gosh.

200
00:10:51,791 --> 00:10:53,250
[voice breaking]
Don't tell me.

201
00:10:53,333 --> 00:10:56,333
Have you been following Tanigaki
all this time

202
00:10:56,416 --> 00:10:58,708
because he had Nihei's gun?

203
00:10:58,791 --> 00:11:00,958
♪

204
00:11:05,666 --> 00:11:07,375
[whimpers]

205
00:11:07,458 --> 00:11:08,583
Ryu!

206
00:11:08,666 --> 00:11:10,333
You're the best dog
in the world!

207
00:11:10,416 --> 00:11:12,125
Ow, what the hell?

208
00:11:12,208 --> 00:11:13,791
Stop biting me, stop biting me,
stop biting me, stop biting me.

209
00:11:13,875 --> 00:11:15,041
[grunts]

210
00:11:15,125 --> 00:11:16,416
That hurt, you little shit!

211
00:11:16,500 --> 00:11:17,916
Get lost!

212
00:11:18,000 --> 00:11:19,791
Looks like Ryu's a loyal dog.

213
00:11:19,875 --> 00:11:23,750
He's not quite ready to forget
the enemy of his master.

214
00:11:23,833 --> 00:11:26,125
♪

215
00:11:33,791 --> 00:11:35,791
Tell me.
What are you gonna do now?

216
00:11:37,833 --> 00:11:41,458
I'll leave once she achieves
her goal, and not before.

217
00:11:42,708 --> 00:11:43,875
Understood.

218
00:11:43,958 --> 00:11:45,333
Asirpa.

219
00:11:45,416 --> 00:11:48,083
Once we're in town,
I'll send Huci a telegram.

220
00:11:49,500 --> 00:11:50,416
That would be great.

221
00:11:50,500 --> 00:11:52,416
[chuckling]

222
00:11:52,500 --> 00:11:54,750
Well, off to Abashiri.

223
00:11:54,833 --> 00:11:56,500
Asirpa, ready to go?

224
00:11:58,000 --> 00:11:59,208
Yeah.

225
00:12:00,416 --> 00:12:03,291
[SUGIMOTO]
Oh-oh-oh-hoy!

226
00:12:08,958 --> 00:12:10,500
[KOITO nervously]
Ohh!

227
00:12:10,583 --> 00:12:13,291
Lieutenant Tsurumi
is gonna scold me.

228
00:12:13,375 --> 00:12:15,625
[sighs] He must've been so mad
when he heard

229
00:12:15,708 --> 00:12:18,083
I let Yoshitake Shiraishi
get away.

230
00:12:18,166 --> 00:12:20,250
Uh, how did he look?

231
00:12:21,500 --> 00:12:22,750
Please, Sergeant.

232
00:12:22,833 --> 00:12:24,666
Tell me the truth.

233
00:12:24,750 --> 00:12:27,708
Did Tsurumi say anything
at all about me?

234
00:12:27,791 --> 00:12:29,333
-Uh...
-Don't say it!

235
00:12:29,416 --> 00:12:31,041
I already know!

236
00:12:31,125 --> 00:12:33,166
[crying]
I'm done for.

237
00:12:33,250 --> 00:12:34,750
I'm gonna be sent
straight off to Abashiri

238
00:12:34,833 --> 00:12:37,041
to watch Shirosuke Inudou!

239
00:12:37,125 --> 00:12:38,791
[crying]

240
00:12:38,875 --> 00:12:41,166
Second Lieutenant,
calm yourself.

241
00:12:41,250 --> 00:12:42,458
Look what I have for you here.

242
00:12:42,541 --> 00:12:44,583
I brought you the photos
you asked for.

243
00:12:44,666 --> 00:12:45,666
[gasps]

244
00:12:45,750 --> 00:12:47,291
[KOITO gasps]

245
00:12:47,375 --> 00:12:49,916
These are so wonderful,
Tsukishima.

246
00:12:50,000 --> 00:12:52,583
This must have been taken
before the Battle of Mukden.

247
00:12:52,666 --> 00:12:54,958
He doesn't have those scars
on his face yet.

248
00:12:55,958 --> 00:12:57,541
[sighs]

249
00:12:57,625 --> 00:12:59,791
I'm jealous of you,
Sergeant Tsukishima.

250
00:12:59,875 --> 00:13:01,375
Huh?

251
00:13:01,458 --> 00:13:05,000
Sometimes I think if only
I'd been born a little earlier

252
00:13:05,083 --> 00:13:07,625
then maybe I could've
fought with him, too.

253
00:13:10,000 --> 00:13:12,125
This is so perfect!

254
00:13:12,208 --> 00:13:16,041
Tsukishima, crush up some rice
to use as glue.

255
00:13:16,125 --> 00:13:17,291
No.

256
00:13:18,375 --> 00:13:20,375
I didn't know you were here,
Second Lieutenant.

257
00:13:20,458 --> 00:13:22,833
[screaming]

258
00:13:23,875 --> 00:13:25,750
[TSURUMI]
Hey.

259
00:13:25,833 --> 00:13:28,458
[speaking in Satsuma dialect]

260
00:13:33,333 --> 00:13:34,625
Goodness, calm down.

261
00:13:34,708 --> 00:13:36,958
I can't make out that high-speed
Satsuma dialect,

262
00:13:37,041 --> 00:13:39,333
so why don't you take
some deep breaths and try again?

263
00:13:39,416 --> 00:13:42,333
[inhales and exhales]

264
00:13:42,416 --> 00:13:45,000
[speaking in Satsuma dialect]

265
00:13:45,958 --> 00:13:47,041
Slow down!

266
00:13:47,125 --> 00:13:48,958
Help me!

267
00:13:49,041 --> 00:13:50,666
Tell him that Shiraishi
did get away

268
00:13:50,750 --> 00:13:52,583
but not before I made
a copy of his tattoos.

269
00:13:52,666 --> 00:13:54,000
[sighs]

270
00:13:54,083 --> 00:13:56,291
He says he made a copy
of Shiraishi's tattoos.

271
00:13:56,375 --> 00:13:57,791
Why am I the only one

272
00:13:57,875 --> 00:13:59,875
who gets the high-speed Satsuma
dialect treatment,

273
00:13:59,958 --> 00:14:01,000
Second Lieutenant Koito?

274
00:14:01,083 --> 00:14:02,458
I'll be honest,

275
00:14:02,541 --> 00:14:04,375
I specifically ordered you
not to kill Shiraishi

276
00:14:04,458 --> 00:14:06,875
because I thought he could
be of great value to us.

277
00:14:06,958 --> 00:14:09,833
Yet, you unfortunately let him
fall into enemy hands.

278
00:14:09,916 --> 00:14:12,416
I'm very disappointed in you,
Second Lieutenant.

279
00:14:12,500 --> 00:14:14,291
[groaning]

280
00:14:20,625 --> 00:14:22,208
♪

281
00:14:26,166 --> 00:14:29,166
Oh-oh. A fashion statement
if I ever saw one.

282
00:14:29,250 --> 00:14:30,583
So that's the skin
of the prisoner

283
00:14:30,666 --> 00:14:32,333
pretending to be Inudou.

284
00:14:32,416 --> 00:14:35,458
I'll admit, this is
a lovely unexpected bonus.

285
00:14:35,541 --> 00:14:36,833
From what we've learned so far,

286
00:14:36,916 --> 00:14:38,583
I think it's safe to say
these tattoos

287
00:14:38,666 --> 00:14:42,125
belonged to the con artist,
Kiyohiro Suzukawa.

288
00:14:42,208 --> 00:14:44,250
Very well done,
Second Lieutenant.

289
00:14:44,333 --> 00:14:45,750
However,

290
00:14:47,041 --> 00:14:48,666
the lines aren't quite right.

291
00:14:48,750 --> 00:14:50,166
[shrieks]

292
00:14:50,250 --> 00:14:52,208
Sunmohan! Sunmohan! Sunmohan!

293
00:14:52,291 --> 00:14:54,666
See, this is what I'm talking
about, Second Lieutenant.

294
00:14:54,750 --> 00:14:56,208
[KOITO]
Sunmohan! Sunmohan! Sunmohan!

295
00:14:56,291 --> 00:14:58,791
As of now, you're off
the Asahikawa Mission.

296
00:14:58,875 --> 00:15:00,791
[groaning]

297
00:15:02,250 --> 00:15:03,708
From now on,

298
00:15:05,333 --> 00:15:07,166
you're going to be
personally helping me

299
00:15:07,250 --> 00:15:08,625
hunt the other prisoners.

300
00:15:08,708 --> 00:15:10,541
[gasping]

301
00:15:12,083 --> 00:15:13,208
Eh?

302
00:15:14,583 --> 00:15:16,541
[whispering]
Tell him that I'll do my best.

303
00:15:16,625 --> 00:15:19,083
He said he'll do his best.
He's thrilled.

304
00:15:20,583 --> 00:15:22,250
[HAJIME]
God, I hate this.

305
00:15:22,333 --> 00:15:24,333
Think very carefully
and tell me,

306
00:15:24,416 --> 00:15:27,375
are you absolutely positive
it was Hyakunosuke Ogata

307
00:15:27,458 --> 00:15:30,416
who was aboard the airship
with Shiraishi and Sugimoto?

308
00:15:30,500 --> 00:15:32,166
-[whispers] Yes.
-Yes.

309
00:15:32,250 --> 00:15:34,333
-[whispering] About Ogata...
-About Ogata...

310
00:15:34,416 --> 00:15:36,291
-He brings disgrace...
-He brings great disgrace...

311
00:15:36,375 --> 00:15:38,750
[BOTH] ...to the noble suicide
of his good father,

312
00:15:38,833 --> 00:15:40,416
former head of
the Seventh Division.

313
00:15:40,500 --> 00:15:43,375
-Even my father feels...
-Even my own father feels...

314
00:15:43,458 --> 00:15:45,000
a very strong distrust

315
00:15:45,083 --> 00:15:47,625
towards the Central Command
for the way they handled it.

316
00:15:47,708 --> 00:15:49,875
They blamed it on
the Seventh Division.

317
00:15:49,958 --> 00:15:52,083
So what could Ogata
be thinking in doing this?

318
00:15:52,166 --> 00:15:54,750
I believe that Second Lieutenant
Koito's father

319
00:15:54,833 --> 00:15:57,416
and General Hanazawa
were both born in Satsuma

320
00:15:57,500 --> 00:15:59,708
and that they were friends,
correct?

321
00:15:59,791 --> 00:16:01,041
[KOITO grunts]

322
00:16:01,125 --> 00:16:03,583
The cause of the suicide
was central command

323
00:16:03,666 --> 00:16:06,291
unfairly laying the full blame
for the high casualties

324
00:16:06,375 --> 00:16:07,500
on 203 Hill

325
00:16:07,583 --> 00:16:09,708
at Lieutenant General
Hanazawa's feet.

326
00:16:09,791 --> 00:16:11,750
I, of course, took it
for granted

327
00:16:11,833 --> 00:16:13,958
that Ogata would fight
for his father's honor

328
00:16:14,041 --> 00:16:16,333
and for that of
the Seventh Division.

329
00:16:16,416 --> 00:16:18,208
That was my great mistake.

330
00:16:23,625 --> 00:16:26,875
[OGATA] At the time, my father
was a lieutenant colonel

331
00:16:26,958 --> 00:16:29,750
in the First Imperial
Guard Regiment.

332
00:16:29,833 --> 00:16:33,375
Given his position, he must've
been pretty irritated

333
00:16:33,458 --> 00:16:36,166
to have an Asakusa geisha
bear his child.

334
00:16:37,166 --> 00:16:40,208
Once his wife bore him
a legitimate son,

335
00:16:40,291 --> 00:16:41,375
my grandmother told me

336
00:16:41,458 --> 00:16:43,375
he stopped coming
to visit entirely.

337
00:16:45,041 --> 00:16:46,666
When I was still a baby,

338
00:16:46,750 --> 00:16:48,291
my grandmother took
my mother and me

339
00:16:48,375 --> 00:16:50,250
back to her home in Ibaraki.

340
00:16:51,250 --> 00:16:54,041
My mother used
to make monkfish stew.

341
00:16:54,125 --> 00:16:58,041
Fugu in the west and monkfish
in the east, they'd say.

342
00:16:58,125 --> 00:17:00,750
It was a local dish
for the lower classes.

343
00:17:00,833 --> 00:17:03,500
I liked it and ate it a lot.

344
00:17:03,583 --> 00:17:07,750
In fact, I ate that stew
pretty much constantly.

345
00:17:07,833 --> 00:17:12,083
Every day in winter, my mother
would get up and make more.

346
00:17:12,166 --> 00:17:16,291
Every afternoon,
a new batch of monkfish stew.

347
00:17:16,375 --> 00:17:19,041
My father said he liked it,
so she'd keep making it,

348
00:17:19,125 --> 00:17:22,208
hoping he'd come back
and eat some with her.

349
00:17:22,291 --> 00:17:24,041
Every day, without fail.

350
00:17:25,291 --> 00:17:27,875
She'd gone crazy at this point,
I think.

351
00:17:27,958 --> 00:17:29,541
[gunshot]

352
00:17:32,625 --> 00:17:35,333
One day, I took an old gun
of my grandfather's

353
00:17:35,416 --> 00:17:37,791
out to the field
and I shot a bird.

354
00:17:42,208 --> 00:17:44,750
I thought
maybe if I brought it home,

355
00:17:44,833 --> 00:17:47,083
my mother wouldn't make
that damned stew.

356
00:17:49,000 --> 00:17:50,958
But no matter
how many birds I hunted,

357
00:17:52,333 --> 00:17:54,791
she refused to stop making it.

358
00:17:57,125 --> 00:17:58,916
I couldn't take it anymore.

359
00:18:00,125 --> 00:18:01,916
When my grandparents were gone,

360
00:18:03,625 --> 00:18:05,375
I put rat poison
in the monkfish stew

361
00:18:05,458 --> 00:18:07,166
and fed it to her.

362
00:18:11,125 --> 00:18:15,208
I figured if my father
had any love left for my mother,

363
00:18:16,291 --> 00:18:17,666
he would come to the funeral.

364
00:18:18,625 --> 00:18:22,583
And one more time,
she'd be with the man she loved.

365
00:18:26,333 --> 00:18:27,208
Wouldn't you know?

366
00:18:27,291 --> 00:18:29,375
♪

367
00:18:30,666 --> 00:18:32,666
You never came.

368
00:18:32,750 --> 00:18:35,125
Are you trying to tell me
that this is revenge

369
00:18:35,208 --> 00:18:37,916
for taking off on you two
all those years ago?

370
00:18:38,916 --> 00:18:42,833
All you did was put your
insane mother out of her misery.

371
00:18:42,916 --> 00:18:45,500
You were sick of her, too.

372
00:18:45,583 --> 00:18:48,166
You're no different than me.

373
00:18:48,250 --> 00:18:50,041
[OGATA] Unfortunately,
children don't get

374
00:18:50,125 --> 00:18:51,500
to choose their parents.

375
00:18:52,625 --> 00:18:56,875
Love is as vague and indefinable
a concept as God.

376
00:18:56,958 --> 00:18:59,625
But I think that if you did have
any love for my mother,

377
00:18:59,708 --> 00:19:01,500
you wouldn't have abandoned her.

378
00:19:03,500 --> 00:19:05,125
I've wondered if maybe

379
00:19:05,208 --> 00:19:08,000
a child born to parents
who don't love each other

380
00:19:08,083 --> 00:19:09,875
comes out missing something.

381
00:19:11,166 --> 00:19:14,875
No matter how impressive
his father's bloodline might be.

382
00:19:16,791 --> 00:19:19,708
If you want proof, just look
at your other child,

383
00:19:19,791 --> 00:19:21,833
the true son your wife gave you.

384
00:19:21,916 --> 00:19:25,458
Second Lieutenant
Yuusaku Hanazawa, a nobleman.

385
00:19:27,041 --> 00:19:29,000
We met after I joined
the military,

386
00:19:29,083 --> 00:19:31,583
and I didn't know how to react.

387
00:19:31,666 --> 00:19:34,125
He insisted on calling me
"big brother,"

388
00:19:34,208 --> 00:19:35,625
showing me deference,

389
00:19:35,708 --> 00:19:38,833
no matter how many times
I told him he outranked me.

390
00:19:38,916 --> 00:19:40,583
He never left me alone.

391
00:19:40,666 --> 00:19:43,958
Said his entire life,
he'd wished he had a brother.

392
00:19:44,041 --> 00:19:45,041
[inaudible]

393
00:19:45,125 --> 00:19:47,708
[OGATA]
That innocent smile.

394
00:19:47,791 --> 00:19:49,500
Ohh!

395
00:19:49,583 --> 00:19:51,208
Looking at it, I realized

396
00:19:51,291 --> 00:19:54,416
that this was a boy
who'd grown up feeling safe...

397
00:19:55,916 --> 00:19:58,666
and loved by his parents.

398
00:19:58,750 --> 00:20:00,625
But with all that love
between them,

399
00:20:00,708 --> 00:20:04,333
his father had no way of knowing
the truth about his death.

400
00:20:05,625 --> 00:20:09,208
How his precious son really died
at 203 Hill.

401
00:20:14,416 --> 00:20:15,583
[gunshot]

402
00:20:17,416 --> 00:20:19,541
I shot him in the back
of the head.

403
00:20:22,458 --> 00:20:25,458
Not out of jealousy
or malice of any kind.

404
00:20:25,541 --> 00:20:29,083
Or a desire to make our father
suffer because of his death.

405
00:20:30,541 --> 00:20:33,625
It was more of an experiment,
I guess.

406
00:20:35,000 --> 00:20:37,750
When he heard about
Yuusaku's death,

407
00:20:37,833 --> 00:20:40,708
would our father think of me,
his other son?

408
00:20:42,000 --> 00:20:44,666
Would he suddenly care
about the child he'd had

409
00:20:44,750 --> 00:20:47,250
with his mistress and abandoned
all those years ago?

410
00:20:47,333 --> 00:20:49,250
♪

411
00:20:52,500 --> 00:20:54,750
Was there a chance
I could've been happy, too,

412
00:20:54,833 --> 00:20:57,333
if things had turned out
differently?

413
00:20:57,416 --> 00:21:00,291
♪

414
00:21:05,041 --> 00:21:07,208
Well, you got one thing right.

415
00:21:07,291 --> 00:21:08,708
[labored breathing]

416
00:21:08,791 --> 00:21:10,666
You're missing something
important deep in your core.

417
00:21:10,750 --> 00:21:12,791
You're a failure of a son.

418
00:21:14,750 --> 00:21:17,166
A curse upon you!

419
00:21:17,250 --> 00:21:19,041
♪

420
00:21:19,125 --> 00:21:20,250
[scoffs]

421
00:21:35,000 --> 00:21:36,125
[gasps]

422
00:21:39,916 --> 00:21:42,458
[TSURUMI] Don't worry,
it's all happening as it should.

423
00:21:42,541 --> 00:21:44,833
The brass will make the Seventh
take responsibility

424
00:21:44,916 --> 00:21:46,208
for his suicide.

425
00:21:46,291 --> 00:21:47,708
It'll be a difficult time
for us,

426
00:21:47,791 --> 00:21:50,166
but you're strong,
and you'll endure.

427
00:21:50,250 --> 00:21:51,916
With an external enemy,

428
00:21:52,000 --> 00:21:55,208
I believe that the Seventh will
come together like never before.

429
00:21:55,291 --> 00:21:57,083
In fact, I predict
that they'll very much

430
00:21:57,166 --> 00:21:58,791
want to make
the only surviving son

431
00:21:58,875 --> 00:22:01,416
of Lieutenant General Hanazawa
into a hero.

432
00:22:01,500 --> 00:22:02,666
I think they'll see in you

433
00:22:02,750 --> 00:22:05,166
something of the god of war
they lost.

434
00:22:05,250 --> 00:22:08,708
So, well done,
Hyakunosuke Ogata.

435
00:22:12,500 --> 00:22:14,875
Very well done, indeed, sir.

436
00:22:17,708 --> 00:22:19,541
[OGATA]
Goddamn seducer.

437
00:24:06,791 --> 00:24:09,666
[NARRATOR]
Next time, "Blue Eyes."

